[normal]No adequate justification
[normal]“Every person within the jurisdiction enjoys the equal protection of our laws. There is no distinction between British nationals and others. He who is subject to English law is entitled to its protect
[normal]ion. This principle has been in the law at least since Lord 
[normal]Mansfied
[normal] freed “the black” in Somerset’s Case (1772) 20 St.Tr.1”
[normal] 
[normal]L
[normal]egal Aid eligibility is based on this very principle: it is currently available for all, regardless of their country of residence, provided their case raises an issue in the legal system of England and Wales and comes within the narrow 
[normal]scope of Legal Aid. 
[normal]This is the ‘connection’ necessary 
[normal]and appropriate 
[normal]for eligibility
[normal]; having a dispute of substance which needs to be resolved in our Courts which cannot otherwise be funded
[normal]. It is fair, sensible and easy to police. It has always been a feature of the Legal 
[normal]Aid system. 
